<br>
A bit more on copyright law, since someone brought up performance.  A copyright is actually a bundle of rights that the copyright owner holds.  This bundle includes the right to perform the work as well as to make and distribute copies.  But, once again, which of these rights is being violated by &quot;selling an item&quot; on ebay?  There's no performance of a copyrighted work.  There IS the sale of a copy of a copyrighted work (assuming the &quot;item&quot; is copyrightable), but that's not a violation, as I discuss above.  <br>
<br>
Someone who possesses an authorized copy of a copyrighted work is free to sell that copy under copyright law.  The thing that might stop them is contract law, if that someone agreed to not sell the copy.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(2/12/02 1:50:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=271.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Interesting</span><hr size=1> In looking over the complaint, I notice that Mythic started the fight.  It sent a letter claiming that the ebay sales violated their trademarks or copyrights (which I have a hard time seeing), and then sent a letter to the plaintiffs threatening to sue them.  The plaintiffs then responded by filing a preemptive lawsuit themselves.  <br>
<br>
The copyright claims are really claims seeking a declaration that certain activities do not violate the federal copyright act.  In essence, they seek a judgment telling Mythic to stop threatening them.  It also gives the federal court jurisidiction. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaurincotg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saurin CoTG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(2/12/02 8:31:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=271.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Interesting</span><hr size=1> I just read the complaint, and other than it is inartfully drafted, my random thoughts are these:<br>
<br>
1)  While the main basis of the complaint is based on a declaration of the application of copyright law, the contractual issues were raised and still may serve as the basis of a defense.  <br>
<br>
2)  If they desired a quick resolution to this situation, I would have filed the complaint in the Eastern District of Virginia, which is commonly referred to as the &quot;Rocket Docket.&quot;  <br>
<br>
3)  From an informational standpoint, reviewing the motion for summary judgment and the attachments would be much more interesting, than the pleading from the plaintiff. <br>
<br>
I will probably think of more later, but will be interesting to see how this all plays out.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaurincotg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saurin CoTG</A> at: 2/12/02 7:35:05 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvinea.showPublicProfile?language=EN>vinea</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(2/12/02 12:08:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=271.topic&index=12>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Interesting</span><hr size=1> &quot;I'm still chuckling at the fact that people actually made a business out of selling abstract MMORPG materials. heh...next thing you know they'll be auctioning their babies' dirty diapers on ebay. =P &quot;<br>
<br>
Given that they are really selling TIME as opposed to anything else I'd have to say it's a valuable commodity.  At least to me.  I have an extremely stupid amount of /played in EQ.  Looking back, I could have done something a lot more productive.  Yet, I do not regret the &quot;good times&quot; of EQ where we did &quot;fun&quot; things.  That's what entertainment is about.<br>
<br>
There are always certain aspects of games that are less fun for some folks than others.  For me, grinding sucks wind.  If I can kill a mob once, the challenge is pretty much gone.  If I can learn how to earn 1 GP, there's little further challenge to figuring out how to do so.  Grinding to GET to the fun parts is to me an unnecessary burden for entertainment...especially computer based entertainment.<br>
<br>
Yes, yes, there is value in being persistent in the pursuit of goals...in the real world.  Burning time to simply burn time in a MMORPG is, well, IMHO silly.<br>
<br>
So, if someone wants to pay these folks to kill a billion greens to get a plat for $100 they've saved dozens of hours.  Likewise if you bought a lvl 50 character you save hundreds of hours of /played.  You then get to enjoy the &quot;fun&quot; part of DAoC...RvR.  <br>
<br>
You'll suck at it but at least every hour spent on the game goes toward learning how to play your class...and not grinding xp until you're blue in the face.  <br>
<br>
I would pay Mythic $200 (about 1 years subscription) to get a lvl 50 character.  They don't sell this option.  Their loss...doubled since I just cancelled DAoC.  <br>
<br>
That's the real way to solve this problem.  Sell equipment and levels for real dollars and tag characters as &quot;BUFFED&quot; or stick em on some different server or something.  For $200 these guys can't afford the time investment to compete and they go out of business.<br>
